              <p>At 96 hours, patients randomized to prolonged prone positioning had a higher total duration proned (56.6 vs. 45.7 h; <italic>P</italic> = 0.02) (<xref rid="tbl2" ref-type="table">Table 2</xref>). Those in the prolonged prone positioning arm had higher mean duration of prone sessions (23.1 vs. 14.9 h; <italic>P</italic> &lt; 0.01) and similar duration of supine sessions (9.0 vs. 11.5 h; <italic>P</italic> = 0.46). Patients in the prolonged prone positioning arm underwent fewer position changes (4.7 vs. 5.7 turns; <italic>P</italic> = 0.05). Respiratory mechanics were similar across groups. There were very few adverse events at 96 hours with no obvious differences between groups.</p>
